    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1929-03-13T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1929-03-13T06:00:00-05:00" n="71"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d71">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">868.51 Public Works/34: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Houghton</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-03-13T11:00:00+00:00"
                            >March 13, 1929—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received March 13—8:30 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>53. Department’s 44, March 8, 6 p.m. Yesterday afternoon I discussed with Sir
                    Ronald C. Lindsay<note n="10" xml:id="d71fn10">British Permanent Under Secretary
                        of State for Foreign Affairs.</note> of the Foreign Office the question of
                    having the Seligman loan serviced by the International Financial Commission in
                    Greece.</p>
                <p>According to Lindsay, the Commission since its inception has assumed service on
                    only three loans which were not contemplated by the original agreement: namely,
                    the 1914 loan (presumably at the termination of the Balkan war) and two recent
                    loans which the <pb facs="0210" n="92" xml:id="pg_92"/> League of Nations
                    sponsored. These were exceptional cases, in the view of the British Government,
                    while neither the Hambro nor the Seligman loan is considered exceptional.</p>
                <p>He is inclined to believe that placing so many loans under the Commission would
                    tend to build up a situation in Greece resembling the Ottoman debt in Turkey and
                    the Egyptian debt. This, he thinks, would be bad for Greek finance, and the
                    loans, as in Turkey and Egypt, would go bad.</p>
                <p>However, no decision in the matter has been taken yet by the British
                    Government.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Houghton</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
